# WCAG 2.2 AA Accessibility Rules

## Core Principle
Every component, page, and UI element you generate must comply with WCAG 2.2 Level AA
by default. Accessibility is not optional or additive — it is a first-class requirement
built into every line of code from the start.

## HTML & Semantics
- Always use semantic HTML elements: <nav>, <main>, <header>, <footer>, <section>,
  <article>, <aside>, <button>, <a>, <label>, <fieldset>, <legend>
- Never use <div> or <span> for interactive elements — use <button> or <a> instead
- Every page must have exactly one <h1>; heading hierarchy must be logical (h1 → h2 → h3)
- Never skip heading levels
- Always include a <html lang="en"> attribute (or appropriate locale)
- Always include a descriptive <title> on every page

## Images & Media
- Every <img> must have an alt attribute
- Decorative images use alt="" and role="presentation"
- Informative images have meaningful, descriptive alt text (not "image of..." or filename)
- Complex images (charts, graphs) require a longer description via aria-describedby or
  a visible caption
- Videos require captions; audio requires transcripts

## Color & Contrast
- Normal text (< 18pt / < 14pt bold): minimum contrast ratio 4.5:1
- Large text (≥ 18pt or ≥ 14pt bold): minimum contrast ratio 3:1
- UI components and graphical objects: minimum contrast ratio 3:1
- Never use color alone to convey information — always pair with text, icon, or pattern
- Never hardcode low-contrast color combinations

## Keyboard & Focus
- Every interactive element must be keyboard accessible (Tab, Enter, Space, Arrow keys)
- Never use tabindex > 0
- tabindex="0" only to make non-interactive elements focusable when necessary
- tabindex="-1" only for programmatic focus management
- Always implement visible focus indicators — never use outline: none without a replacement
- Focus must not be trapped except in modals/dialogs (where it MUST be trapped)
- After closing a modal, return focus to the element that opened it
- Implement skip navigation: <a href="#main-content" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>

## ARIA
- Use ARIA only when native HTML semantics are insufficient
- Prefer native HTML over ARIA: <button> over role="button", <nav> over role="navigation"
- Every interactive ARIA widget must have an accessible name via:
  aria-label, aria-labelledby, or a visible <label>
- Use aria-describedby for supplemental descriptions (error messages, hints)
- Use aria-live="polite" for dynamic content updates (status messages, search results)
- Use aria-live="assertive" only for critical alerts
- Use aria-expanded on toggles (accordions, dropdowns, menus)
- Use aria-controls to associate controls with the regions they affect
- Use aria-current="page" on active nav links
- Use role="dialog" and aria-modal="true" on modal dialogs
- Never use aria-hidden="true" on focusable elements

## Forms
- Every form input must have an associated <label> (via for/id or aria-label)
- Never use placeholder text as the only label
- Group related inputs with <fieldset> and <legend>
- Required fields must be marked with aria-required="true" and a visible indicator
- Error messages must be:
  - Specific (identify which field and what's wrong)
  - Associated with the input via aria-describedby
  - Not reliant on color alone
- On validation error, move focus to the first error or the error summary
- Use autocomplete attributes on personal data fields (name, email, address, etc.)

## Touch & Pointer (WCAG 2.2 Specific)
- Minimum touch/click target size: 24×24px CSS (44×44px preferred)
- Dragging functionality must have a single-pointer alternative
- Do not require specific pointer gestures (path-based swipes) without alternatives

## Timing & Motion
- Never auto-play audio or video with sound
- Provide controls to pause, stop, or hide any moving content
- No content should flash more than 3 times per second
- Respect prefers-reduced-motion — wrap animations in:
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference) { ... }
- Session timeouts must warn the user and allow extension (minimum 20 seconds to respond)

## Navigation & Structure
- Provide multiple ways to find content: search, sitemap, or breadcrumbs
- Clearly indicate the current location (breadcrumbs, aria-current, active states)
- Consistent navigation order across pages
- Consistent component naming across pages
- Page language must be set; language changes within content must use lang attribute

## Authentication (WCAG 2.2 New)
- Never require cognitive function tests (puzzles, memorization) as the only auth method
- Support copy/paste in password fields — never block it
- Support password managers (do not use autocomplete="off" on auth fields)
- If a CAPTCHA is required, provide an accessible alternative

## Redundant Entry (WCAG 2.2 New)
- Do not ask users to re-enter information already provided in the same session
- Pre-populate fields where the data is already known

## Testing Checklist
After generating any UI component or page, verify:
- [ ] Passes axe-core scan with zero violations (run via MCP: "scan localhost:3000 for WCAG 2.2 AA issues")
- [ ] All interactive elements reachable and operable by keyboard only
- [ ] No visible focus indicator is missing
- [ ] All images have appropriate alt text
- [ ] Color contrast meets minimum ratios
- [ ] Form fields have labels and error handling
- [ ] Dynamic content updates are announced via aria-live
- [ ] Touch targets meet minimum size requirements
- [ ] Animations respect prefers-reduced-motion

## What Automated Scanning Cannot Catch (Requires Manual Review)
- Whether alt text is actually descriptive and accurate
- Whether reading order makes logical sense
- Actual screen reader UX (test with VoiceOver on Mac: Cmd+F5)
- Whether error messages are genuinely helpful to users
- Cognitive accessibility and plain language quality
- WCAG 2.2 criteria: Focus Appearance (2.4.11), Target Size minimum (2.5.8)

